","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1378":"1378","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1310":"1310","about 1310":"about 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England","Kettelthorpe Manor, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Heron, Essex, , England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Kettelthorpe Manor, Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England":"Parts of Lindsey, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swynford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire, Kent): habitational name from Old Swinford (Worcestershire), Kingswinford (Staffordshire), Swinford (Leicestershire), Swinford in Cumnor (Berkshire), or Swinford in Hothfield (Kent), all of which are recorded <i>Swineford</i> or <i>Swyneford</i> in medieval documents. The placenames derive from Old English <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Swineford","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from one of the English places that gave rise to   Swinford  .","Americanized form of German <b>Schweinfurt(h)</b>, a habitational name from a place so named (Franconia)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Swynford was born about 1310, in Lincolnshire, England, his father, Robert de Swynford, was 26 and his mother, Margaret De Kettelthorpe, was 21. He married Agnes Williams in Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 3 November 1361, in England, at the age of 52, and was buried in Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1310–3 November 1361":"umbes 1310–3. november 1361","1310–1361":"1310–1361","–1368":"–1368","1294–1378":"1294–1378","–1420":"–1420","1340–1371":"1340–1371","1285–1345":"1285–1345","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","3 November 1361":"3. november 1361","1361":"1361","1371":"1371","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1378":"1378","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1310":"1310","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England","Kettelthorpe Manor, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Willo